Weight loss with the keto diet.

Keto diet not allow for carbohydrates to be converted to glucose.
Keto diet makes people lose weight in four different ways:
- by making you eat fewer calories,
- mobilizing fat from your body,
- improving insulin sensitivity
- reducing the hunger hormone ghrelin.

The ketogenic diet is a low-carbohydrate, high-fat diet that shares many similarities with another very popular diet of weight loss called the Atkins Diet. This allows you to get all of your energy needs met while also losing weight in the process. If you are trying for an extended period of time to lose weight or if exercise isn't enough, then I recommend exploring the Ketogenic Diet as well!

The classic Ketogenic Meal Plan is developed by Dr. Eric Westman who used it in his own patients and clinical research studies before publishing it to the outside world.

Boston Globe, 6 May 2022: Hamilton-Wenham Regional High School‚Äôs junior prom was cut short on April 28, 2022 after one or more students were heard yelling a racial slur while a song was playing, school officials said.

‚ÄúWhile the music was playing and students were dancing, one or more students yelled the N-word,‚Äù Superintendent Eric Tracy said Monday in a letter to Hamilton-Wenham families. ‚ÄúThis racial slur was heard by a number of our students and was very upsetting to them.‚Äù

Tracy said high school principal Bryan Menegoni made the decision to end the prom early and address all of the students directly. He immediately opened an investigation of the incident.

School officials also have asked the police to investigate, he said.

Tracy said the song that was playing when the student (or students) yelled the slur was appropriate for radio. WCVB reported the song was ‚ÄúCaroline‚Äù by Anime.

‚ÄúUnfortunately, there is some considerable deflection happening on social media,‚Äù Tracy said in the letter. ‚ÄúSome people are pointing at the DJ and administration for playing/approving the song in question. All music played at the prom was radio appropriate as it is a standard of the DJ before being hired.‚Äù

You can now officially file President Joe Biden‚Äôs claim that he‚Äôs ‚Äúnever spoken‚Äù to his son Hunter about his business activities with his claims that inflation is ‚Äútransitory‚Äù and the border is ‚Äúunder control.‚Äù

The Post reported that Joe allegedly agreed to pay more than $800,000 in legal bills Hunter racked up, including bills related to his overseas businesses. This comes on the heels of revelations that Hunter alleged his father was taking half his salary.

It would be literally impossible to set up these arrangements without talking business. So the prez has been outright lying. Just as Hunter‚Äôs business partner Tony Bobulinski said months ago.

Want more evidence? Consider The Post‚Äôs revelation of the direct sit-down Joe had as veep with another Hunter partner, Eric Schwerin, then serving as president of investment fund Rosemont Seneca Partners.

We still don‚Äôt know what they discussed. Or what was said on the 19 occasions Schwerin visited the White House and other official locations from 2009 to 2015. Asked about these shady details, chief Biden flack Jen Psaki responded: ‚ÄúI don‚Äôt have any information on that.‚Äù The future MSNBC star doesn‚Äôt want to know.

Even the Secret Service is playing dumb. It recently and unbelievably told The Post it has no relevant records on who‚Äôs visited the prez at his Delaware homes, as if knowing weren‚Äôt central to its job.

And these are just the latest signs that Hunter (like Joe‚Äôs brother Jim) was running an influence-peddling business with his dad as the chief inventory. For one, we now know Joe wrote college recommendation letters for kids of one of Hunter‚Äôs Chinese associates, met with Hunter‚Äôs other business partner Devon Archer and also an exec of Burisma, the Ukrainian energy company that paid Hunter for $50k a month as a ‚Äúboard member.‚Äù

From Government Accountability & Oversight

Government transparency group Energy Policy Advocates (EPA) filed suit on Thursday against the Biden White House‚Äôs Office of Science and Technology Policy‚Äôs refusal to produce correspondence pertaining to one of an increasing number of initiatives to combat opposition to the administration‚Äôs political agenda as ‚Äúdisinformation.‚Äù

Specifically, EPA argued:

‚ÄúThe request sought certain described correspondence of two named officials, Eric Lander and Jane Lubchenco, over an eight-week period of time, on any email account used at any time for work-related correspondence, that was sent to one or more of six or five named outside parties, respectively. This request pertained to an OSTP ‚Äúevent on countering climate change denial and delay‚Äù in which the Office brought in political activists to discuss, e.g., social science which might explain political opposition to their demands. See, e.g., Maxine Joselow, ‚ÄúWhite House schedules first event on countering climate change denial and delay,‚Äù Washington Post, February 24, 2022. ‚Ä¶

The requested records will inform the public of high-profile ethics revelations at OSTP and media coverage thereof, and also the genesis of a tendentious event and campaign out of OSTP. ‚Äúin this request that one of the two officials, Ms. Lubchenco, had been shown during a prior stint as a political appointee in a different agency during a previous administration to have continued to use her previous employer‚Äôs http://‚Äú.edu‚Äù email account for official federal work-related correspondence, and also detailed Defendant‚Äôs own history, during that same administration, of employees having been found to engage in the practice of using non-official email accounts for work-related correspondence.‚Äù
